liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It's all got to do with the falling price of iron ore futures. They've taken a hit in response to weaker-than-expected steel consumption, completion of pre-holiday restocking and possible output restrictions. On the Singapore Exchange, benchmark October iron ore was 3.2% lower at $117.25 a tonne. Several factors have jointly contributed to the broad weakness in raw materials, said Pei Hao, a Shanghai-based analyst at international brokerage firm FIS. "It becomes increasingly clear that demand has hit the ceiling amid weaker-than-expected steel sales for September and October, and after the replenishment of raw materials to meet production needs over the upcoming week-long holiday break came to an end," he said. Weighing on prices of the key steelmaking ingredient are also "concerns of tighter monetary policy", analysts at ANZ bank said in a note. — with Reuters
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Why are miners being dragged down on the market today?

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The federal opposition has described the employment white paper as a "missed opportunity". The government has outlined measures it plans to introduce to ensure Australians have the skills they need for future jobs, and incentives to keep people working. It includes allowing pensioners and veterans to work more hours before their pension is reduced and accelerating the take up of higher apprenticeships in priority areas. Shadow Treasurer Angus Taylor says while some proposals have merit, he's concerned about other government plans. "We do see this white paper as missed opportunity," he said. "We see IR reforms coming forward from this government that business has universally condemned. "They are the wrong initiatives for the time. If we are to knock down those barriers to work we need to make sure we have the right IR policies in place."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: White Paper 'a missed opportunity', Coalition says

children.content: The federal opposition has described the employment white paper as a "missed opportunity".

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A future hydrogen terminal near Whyalla has secured funding commitments from the state and federal governments, with expectations of "large-scale" global exports before the end of the decade. The state and federal governments have ratified funding arrangements for a so-called "hydrogen hub" at Port Bonython, committing to a combined $100 million spend, in addition to private sector funding. The location, in South Australia's Upper Spencer Gulf region, was earmarked by the previous federal government before last year's election for future hydrogen projects. Among them is what Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has described as a "large-scale export terminal" for "green" hydrogen. The government expects the local industry to produce as much as 1.8 million tonnes of hydrogen by 2030, and said it could also power steel production at the nearby Whyalla steelworks, which is owned by British billionaire Sanjeev Gupta.
